  "answer": "**Takhallus** (also spelled *takhallus*; plural: *takhallusat*) is the Urdu/Persian poetic tradition's term for a poet's pseudonym or pen-name. It is conventionally inscribed—often self-referentially—in the *maqta*, the closing couplet (or *maqtaʿ*) of a ghazal, where the poet signs or identifies themselves, frequently with wit, pathos, or philosophical reflection.[^1][^2]\n\nThe word itself appears explicitly only once in the entire Falsafa corpus (in Ghalib's *Diwan*), used metaphorically for a heart once known as \"Saboori\" (the Patient One).[^3]\n\n### Instances by poet:\n- **Mirza Ghalib** (takhallus: **Asad**): Ubiquitous in his *Diwan-e-Ghalib* (239 ghazals), always in the maqta. E.g., ghazal 4's maqta:  \n  > Har rang mein jala **Asad**-e-fitna-e-intezaar  \n  > Parwana-e-tajalli-e-shama-e-zahoor tha[^4]  \n  (Trans.: \"Asad, consumed by waiting's restless, burning might, / A moth before the flame of sacred light was.\"[^5])\n\n- **Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq** (takhallus: **Zauq**): Appears in his *Diwan-e-Zauq* (60 ghazals), e.g., ghazal 5's title and presumed maqta: *Ae Zauq waqt naale ke rakh le jigar pe haath* (\"O Zauq, at this moment of lament, place your hand on your liver/heart\").[^6] (No full chapter read, but title indicates standard maqta usage; \"Zauq\" recurs thematically in searches, though not always capitalized as takhallus.)\n\n- **Allama Iqbal** (takhallus: **Iqbal**): Frequent in *Bang-e-Dara* (Parts 1–3; 100+ poems/ghazals). E.g., Part 1, ghazal 2's maqta:  \n  > Mere ashaar ae **Iqbal** kyun pyaare na hon mujh ko  \n  > Mere toote hue dil ke yeh dard angez naale hain[^7]  \n  (Trans.: \"O **Iqbal**, why should my verse seem in vain? / They are my broken heart's own cries of pain.\"[^8])  \n  Many others, e.g., Part 1 ch. 4, 6.[^9]\n\nNo other explicit *takhallus* definitions or additional instances for these poets appear in the corpus (37 works total). Iqbal's usage sometimes extends philosophically beyond strict ghazal maqtas.[^10]",
